The algebraic structure of the seventy-two Melakartas
[Author name withheld for blind review]
Abstract
The seventy-two Melakarta parent scales of Carnatic music admit a natural twelve-bit encoding as popcount-seven vectors in \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12} subject to the classical constraints of Venkaṭamakhin's c. 1635 derivation. We show that this encoding supports a rich interlocking collection of algebraic and combinatorial symmetries. A Klein four-group generated by madhyama swap (K_{1}) and Sa-Pa-fixing pitch-class complementation (K_{2}) acts freely on the seventy-two set, partitioning it into eighteen orbits of size four. The Hamming-distance-2 graph on the Melakartas is 9-regular, and its full pairwise distance distribution (324, 936, 936, 324, 36) over the \binom{72}{2}=2556 pairs is forced by three elementary structural facts. We construct an explicit Gray-code Hamiltonian path through all seventy-two Melakartas that achieves the minimum possible number of madhyama crossings. We identify the unique Z-related pair of Forte set-classes, 7-Z18 and 7-Z38, realised among the Melakartas, carried by Navanītam, Divyamaṇi, and Dhavaḷāmbari. We refine the classical forty-count vivadi predicate of Govindācārya and Sambamurthy to an "extremal tetrachord nibble" condition that exactly reproduces the count and identifies a musically-coherent fourteen-Melakarta exception set including Kharaharapriyā, Harikāmbhoji, and Naṭabhairavi. An empirical test against the Wikipedia janya-raga catalog (N=902) finds that Forte-class population size robustly correlates with per-Melakarta compositional productivity (Spearman \rho=+0.46, p<10^{-4}, robust to reasonable outlier-exclusion checks). Our methodological precedent is Sridharan et al. (2010); we extend their programme of applying modern combinatorial algebra to Sanskrit-era Indian musicology from rhythmic pratyayas to scale-level melās.
Keywords. Carnatic music; Melakarta; Klein four-group; Hamming graph; Gray code; Forte set-class; Z-relation; vivadi; pitch-class set theory; combinatorial musicology.
1 Introduction
The 72 Melakarta ragas are the parent scales of the South Indian (Carnatic) musical tradition. Established in their present form in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries by Venkaṭamakhin (Venkaṭamakhin, c. 1635) and Govindācārya (Govindācārya, c. 1750), they form a combinatorially-complete catalog of seven-note scales containing the two fixed tones Sa and Pa together with a specific choice of one Ma (semitone 5 or 6) and two further notes in each tetrachord. This choice structure yields the familiar factorisation 2\times6\times6=72.
The 72-set has attracted occasional attention from mathematical writers (Imai et al., 2021; Padi et al., 2018; Baez, 2023), but its algebraic structure has not been developed in the combinatorial-algebraic idiom of modern pitch-class set theory (Forte, 1973a; Rahn, 1980; Morris, 1987). This paper is such a development. Its five principal results, each the subject of a subsequent section, are: (i) A Klein four-group \mathcal{K}=\{0,K_{1},K_{2},K_{3}\} acting freely on the 72 Melakartas, with 18 orbits of size 4 given by \{n,37-n,36+n,73-n\} for n\in\{1,...,18\} (Section 3). (ii) The Hamming-distance-2 graph G on the Melakartas is 9-regular with 324 edges, and has distance distribution (N_{2},N_{4},N_{6},N_{8},N_{10})=(324,936,936,324,36) completely forced by three elementary structural facts (Section 4). (iii) An explicit Gray-code Hamiltonian path through all 72 Melakartas, constructed by Warnsdorff's heuristic, using the minimum possible number of madhyama crossings (Section 5). (iv) The identification of a unique Z-related pair of Forte set-classes, 7-Z18 and 7-Z38, realised among the Melakartas, carried by the three melas {40, 48, 49} (Section 6). (v) A bit-structural refinement of the classical 40-count vivadi predicate to an "extremal tetrachord nibble" condition, with a principled 14-mela exception set (Section 7).
These results are independent of one another in logical content but share a common formal apparatus, developed in Section 2: a twelve-bit encoding of each Melakarta's pitch-class set under a mirrored-endianness convention that turns the classical pairings n\mapsto n\pm36 and n\mapsto 73-n into pure XOR operations on \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}.
2 Preliminaries: the Melakarta system and its binary encoding
2.1 The Melakarta system
A Melakarta raga is a seven-note ascending-descending scale of the form Sa, R_{i}, G_{j}, M_{k}, P, D_{l}, N_{m} where Sa (semitone 0) and Pa (semitone 7) are fixed, Ma is one of M_{1} (semitone 5) or M_{2} (semitone 6), and the remaining four notes are chosen from a constrained set of enharmonic positions (see e.g. Sambamurthy (1963-1973)). In detail, the six admissible (R, G)-tetrachord pairs are (R_{1},G_{1}), (R_{1},G_{2}), (R_{1},G_{3}), (R_{2},G_{2}), (R_{2},G_{3}), (R_{3},G_{3})—these are the six pairs of distinct positions drawn from the set of four chromatic lower-tetrachord slots—and similarly six (D, N)-pairs in the upper tetrachord. The product 2\times6\times6=72 gives the total count, originally due to Venkaṭamakhin (Venkaṭamakhin, c. 1635). Govindācārya (Govindācārya, c. 1750) gave the canonical kaṭapayādi-sankhyā numbering: Melakarta n=6(c-1)+p has chakra c\in\{1,...,12\} and within-chakra position p\in\{1,...,6\}, with M_{1} if c\le6 and M_{2} if c\ge7; the (R, G)-type is determined by ((c-1) \bmod 6) + 1 and the (D, N)-type by p.
2.2 The twelve-bit representation
Each Melakarta determines a seven-element subset of the twelve chromatic pitch classes {0,1,..., 11}. We fix a bijection \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}\leftrightarrow\mathcal{P}(\{0,...,11\}) and treat words interchangeably as binary vectors, three-digit hexadecimal numbers, and pitch-class sets.
