In the lower tetrachord (Sa through G_{3}), higher bit indices correspond to lower chromatic semitones. In the upper tetrachord (D_{1} through N_{3}), higher bit indices correspond to higher chromatic semitones. The two tetrachords therefore have opposite bit orders—hence mirrored. The madhyama bits, M_{1} at bit 5 and M_{2} at bit 6, sit between the two tetrachords.
This convention differs from Ring's LSB-at-root convention (Ring, accessed 2024-2026) by a bit reversal on the upper tetrachord. The two conventions are mathematically equivalent representations of the same pitch-class set; no musical fact depends on the convention chosen. The mirrored convention has the pedagogical advantage that hex nibbles carry coherent musical chunks, and the algebraic advantage that the two involutions developed below—madhyama twinning and antipodal complement—act as pure XOR on \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}. Under a convention in which the upper and lower tetrachords were read in the same direction, the antipodal complement would act as a bit reversal on the ten non-Sa non-Pa bits, and the Klein-four structure of Section 3 would not close as a subgroup of (\mathbb{F}_{2}^{12},\oplus).
Example 2.1 (Worked encoding). Māyāmāḷavagauḷa (Melakarta 15) contains the semitones {0, 1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11}, i.e. S, R_{1}, G_{3}, M_{1}, P, D_{1}, N_{3}. Under the mirrored-endianness table, these set bits 11, 10, 7, 5, 4, 0, 3 respectively, yielding the binary word 1100 1011 1001 = \mathtt{0xCB9}.
