3 The Klein-four group action on the Melakarta set
This section states and proves the paper's first main result: that two musically-motivated involutions—the madhyama swap and the chromatic complement—generate a Klein four-group \mathbb{Z}/2\times\mathbb{Z}/2 acting freely on the seventy-two Melakarta encodings, partitioning them into eighteen orbits of size four.
3.1 Two involutions
The first involution is the madhyama swap. Fix K_{1}=\mathtt{0x060}\in\mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}. Under the mirrored-endianness convention, K_{1} has exactly two bits set, at positions 5 and 6, corresponding to M_{1} and M_{2}.
Proposition 3.1 (Madhyama twinning). For every n\in\{1,2,...,36\}, E(n)\oplus E(n+36)=K_{1}, and in particular d(E(n), E(n+36))=2.
Proof. By construction of Govindācārya's numbering, Melakarta n+36 is obtained from Melakarta n by replacing M_{1} with M_{2} while keeping Sa, Pa, and all R-G and D-N bits unchanged. The XOR difference therefore sets exactly bits 5 and 6, which is K_{1}. \square
This XOR pattern is already implicit in Venkaṭamakhin's 2\times6\times6 factorisation (Venkaṭamakhin, c. 1635, Ch. IV) and is the foundation of his original derivation of the seventy-two count. The novelty below lies not in Proposition 3.1, but in combining it with a second, independent involution.
The second involution is the antipodal complement. Fix K_{2}=\mathtt{0x7EF}\in\mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}. Under mirrored endianness, K_{2} has ten bits set—all bits except those corresponding to Sa (bit 11) and Pa (bit 4). XOR-ing a twelve-bit word with K_{2} therefore fixes the Sa and Pa bits and flips every other bit.
Proposition 3.2 (Antipodal complement). For every n\in\{1,2,...,72\}, E(n)\oplus E(73-n)=K_{2}, and in particular d(E(n), E(73-n))=10.
Proof. XOR-ing by K_{2} fixes the Sa and Pa bits and flips the ten remaining bits. A Melakarta encoding has Sa and Pa set plus exactly five of the ten remaining bits set; its K_{2}-image has Sa and Pa set plus the other five bits. To show the image is another valid Melakarta, we examine the three regions of the encoding. The madhyama region consists of bits 5 and 6; the original encoding has exactly one of these set, and flipping both exchanges M_{1} for M_{2}. The lower R-G region consists of bits 10, 9, 8, 7; the six admissible popcount-2 patterns {\mathtt{0xC}, \mathtt{0xA}, \mathtt{0x9}, \mathtt{0x6}, \mathtt{0x5}, \mathtt{0x3}} form three complementary pairs {\mathtt{0xC}, \mathtt{0x3}}, {\mathtt{0xA}, \mathtt{0x5}}, {\mathtt{0x9}, \mathtt{0x6}}, and flipping all four bits sends R-G type i to type 7-i. The identical argument applies to the upper D-N region. Each image is therefore another valid Melakarta. To identify the image with Melakarta 73-n, observe that n=6(c-1)+p satisfies 73-n = 6(12-c)+(7-p), which has chakra 13-c (madhyama swapped, R-G type complemented) and position 7-p (D-N type complemented). This matches the operation above. \square
Remark 3.3. The operation K_{2} should not be confused with chromatic inversion about Sa, which acts on pitch classes by s\mapsto(-s) \bmod 12. Chromatic inversion about Sa does not preserve Pa—it sends Pa (semitone 7) to M_{1} (semitone 5)—and therefore does not send Melakartas to Melakartas. The operation K_{2} is instead pitch-class complementation within the ten-element set of non-Sa non-Pa semitones, holding Sa and Pa fixed.
The antipodal pairing n\leftrightarrow73-n appears as a visual pattern in Mukund's widely-reproduced online chart of the Melakartas (Mukund, accessed 2024-2026), where it is described as the operation that exchanges each Melakarta with the one whose swaras are "opposite, excepting Sa and Pa." Proposition 3.2 gives an algebraic reason for this observation.
3.2 The Klein four-group and its orbits
Define K_{3}=K_{1}\oplus K_{2}=\mathtt{0x78F}.
Proposition 3.4. The set \mathcal{K}=\{0,K_{1},K_{2},K_{3}\} is a subgroup of (\mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}) isomorphic to \mathbb{Z}/2\times\mathbb{Z}/2.
Proof. XOR on \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12} is associative, commutative, and every element is its own inverse. The set is closed under XOR and contains the identity. Since none of K_{1}, K_{2}, K_{3} equals the sum of the other two, the group is not cyclic.
Theorem 3.5 (Klein-four action on Melakartas). The group \mathcal{K} acts freely on E(\{1,...,72\})\subset\mathbb{F}_{2}^{12} partitioning it into exactly eighteen orbits of size four.
Proof. Closure and orbit-to-orbit consistency follow from Propositions 3.1 and 3.2; freeness is immediate because no nonzero K_{i} fixes any Melakarta; 72/4=18 completes the count.
Corollary 3.6 (Orbit structure). For each n\in\{1,2,...,18\}, the set \{n,37-n,36+n,73-n\} is a Klein-four orbit, and the eighteen orbits indexed by n are pairwise disjoint.
Proof. For 1\le n\le18: applying K_{1} sends n to n+36; applying K_{2} sends n to 73-n; applying K_{3} sends n to 37-n. The ranges {1,..., 18}, {19,..., 36}, {37, 54}, {55,..., 72} are pairwise disjoint, so the 18 orbits exhaust {1,..., 72}.
3.3 Relation to prior work
The seventy-two count is Venkaṭamakhin's, and the K_{1} generator is a reformulation of the 2-factor in his 2\times6\times6 derivation (Venkaṭamakhin, c. 1635, 2010). Proposition 3.1 is therefore not a new result but the restatement of a classical observation in \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12} language.
The K_{2} generator is visually anticipated in Mukund's chart (Mukund, accessed 2024-2026) and discussed qualitatively in Nagarajan (2015). What is novel is the composition of K_{1} and K_{2} into a Klein four-group acting on the Melakartas, and the orbit decomposition of Corollary 3.6. We are not aware of a published source that assembles these observations into a group action, names the eighteen orbits, or relates the orbit structure to the distribution of musical prominence in the Melakarta catalog.
The present work also connects to the broader programme of formal analyses of the 72-set. Imai et al. (2021) propose an icosahedral representation of the Melakartas in which the icosahedral rotation group (of order 60, isomorphic to the alternating group A_5) acts on scale content via combinatorial operations on icosahedron faces [1]; their symmetry group and ours (the Boolean \mathbb{Z}/2 \times \mathbb{Z}/2 model) arise from independent combinatorial starting points, and we have not been able to express either as a function on the other. Padi et al. (2018) give a category-theoretic treatment of Carnatic raga structure in which scales appear as objects in a monoidal category but scale-level group actions are not developed. Sridharan et al. (2010) establish the methodology of formalising Sanskrit-era combinatorial musicology, applied to Śārṅgadeva's tāna and tāla pratyayas rather than Melakartas. Our paper extends this methodology to the Melakarta system.
4 A Hamming graph on the Melakarta system
Let G be the graph on the 72 Melakartas whose edges connect pairs at Hamming distance exactly 2 in the 12-bit encoding.
4.1 Regularity
Theorem 4.1. The Hamming-distance-2 graph G on the seventy-two Melakartas is 9-regular. For every Melakarta m, the nine distance-2 neighbours of m decompose as 4 (R-G-type swaps) + 4 (D-N-type swaps) + 1 (madhyama swap).
Proof. Partition the twelve bit positions into five regions: S=\{11\} (Sa), P=\{4\} (Pa), L=\{10,9,8,7\} (R-G), M=\{5,6\} (madhyama), U=\{3,2,1,0\} (D-N). Every Melakarta has Sa and Pa set, so a distance-2 move cannot involve bits 11 or 4. The remaining ten bits carry popcounts (2,1,2) over (L, M, U); a distance-2 move chooses one of the 5 set bits and one of the 5 unset bits to flip. A valid Melakarta requires L-popcount 2, M-popcount 1, U-popcount 2. Hence the move must keep the popcounts of all three regions unchanged, which forces both flipped bits to lie in the same region. Counting intra-region moves: \binom{2}{1}\binom{2}{1}=4 within L, 4 within U, and 1 within M, giving 9 neighbours.
Corollary 4.2. The graph G has exactly 324 edges. Proof. |E(G)|=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{v}deg(v)=\frac{1}{2}\cdot72\cdot9=324 \square
4.2 The distance distribution
Theorem 4.4. Let N_{d} denote the number of unordered pairs of Melakartas at Hamming distance d. Then (N_2, N_4, N_6, N_8, N_{10}) = (324, 936, 936, 324, 36), and N_{d}=0 for all other values of d. In particular, the diameter of G equals 10; the 36 distance-10 pairs are exactly the Klein-four antipodal pairs of Proposition 3.2.
Proof. We formalize the distance distribution by decomposing the Hamming distance between any two Melakartas into independent contributions across the lower (L), madhyama (M), and upper (U) localized nibble regions. The distance distribution within the 6-element L and U tetrachord regions generates the identical polynomial P_{L,U}(x) = 6 + 24x^2 + 6x^4. This polynomial represents 6 distance-0 pairs (identity), 24 distance-2 pairs, and 6 distance-4 pairs (ordered, utilizing a 6 \times 6 matrix). The binary M region generates the simpler polynomial P_M(x) = 2 + 2x^2. The full ordered distance distribution across the entire vector space is therefore the mathematical tensor product of these regional polynomials:
Expanding the tensor product of the lower and upper tetrachords yields: (36 + 288x^2 + 648x^4 + 288x^6 + 36x^8)
Multiplying this intermediate polynomial by the madhyama distribution P_M(x) results in: (36 + 288x^2 + 648x^4 + 288x^6 + 36x^8) \times (2 + 2x^2) = 72 + 648x^2 + 1872x^4 + 1872x^6 + 648x^8 + 72x^{10}
Because this polynomial represents ordered pairs, dividing the non-zero degree coefficients by 2 directly transitions the data to the final unordered pairwise distance sequence: 324 pairs at distance 2, 936 pairs at distance 4, 936 pairs at distance 6, 324 pairs at distance 8, and 36 pairs at distance 10. The 36 distance-10 pairs correspond to d_{L}=d_{U}=4 and d_{M}=2, which forces the pair to be antipodal under K_{2}. \square
5 A Gray-code traversal of the 72-set
A Gray code on a graph is a Hamiltonian path: a linear ordering of the vertices in which consecutive vertices are adjacent. For our graph G, a Gray code is a permutation (m_{0},m_{1},...,m_{71}) of the 72 Melakartas such that consecutive pairs (m_{i},m_{i+1}) are at Hamming distance exactly 2.
5.1 Hex-sorted order is not a Gray code
The naive ordering by kaṭapayādi number n=1,2,...,72 is not a Gray code: consecutive Melakartas are generically at Hamming distance 4 or higher, because the kaṭapayādi indexing cycles through D-N type before updating R-G type, producing distance-4 jumps at each chakra boundary.
5.2 A Hamiltonian path via Warnsdorff's heuristic
Theorem 5.1. The Hamming-distance-2 graph G on the 72 Melakartas admits a Hamiltonian path. In particular, there exists a permutation (m_{0},m_{1},...,m_{71}) of \{1,...,72\} with d(E(m_{i}), E(m_{i+1}))=2 for i=0,1,...,70.
Proof. By exhibition. Apply Warnsdorff's heuristic (Pohl, 1967; Squirrel and Cull, 2002) to G starting from Kanakangi (Melakarta 1): at each step, move to the neighbour with the smallest number of unvisited neighbours remaining, breaking ties by Melakarta number. A single depth-first search using this heuristic (executed in under one second on commodity hardware) produces a path which visits all 72 vertices with every consecutive pair at Hamming distance exactly 2.
Proposition 5.2 (Minimum madhyama crossings). The Warnsdorff path of Theorem 5.1 uses exactly one transition of the madhyama-swap type (XOR=K_{1}). This is the minimum possible number of madhyama crossings in any Hamiltonian path of G.
Proof. The 36 M-swap edges form a perfect matching between the M_{1} side \{m:m\le36\} and the M_{2} side \{m:m\ge37\}; they are the only edges of G crossing this bipartition. Any Hamiltonian path visiting vertices on both sides must traverse at least one such edge. The Warnsdorff path crosses exactly once (from Melakarta 29 to Melakarta 65 at step 35), which is therefore minimal. \square
6 The unique Z-relation
6.1 Forte set-classes among the 72
We now place the Melakartas in the framework of pitch-class set theory (Forte, 1973a; Rahn, 1980; Morris, 1987). Two pitch-class sets A,B\subset\mathbb{Z}/12 are T_n-related if B=A+t for some t, and T_nI-related if B=-A+t for some t. The resulting equivalence classes are the Forte set-classes.
Proposition 6.1 (Forte-class distribution). The 72 Melakartas realise exactly 24 distinct Forte set-classes. The number of classes of each size k, for k=1,...,7 is (singletons, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7-class) = (8, 4, 3, 4, 1, 2, 2).
6.2 The unique Z-relation
Two pitch-class sets are Z-related if they share the same interval-class vector but are not equivalent under any T_{n} or T_{n}I (Forte, 1973b, §1.10). For heptachords, Forte catalogued three Z-related pairs: 7-Z12/Z36, 7-Z17/Z37, and 7-Z18/Z38.
Theorem 6.2. Among the 72 Melakartas, exactly one Z-relation is realised: the pair (7-Z18, 7-Z38). The three Melakartas participating are 40 (Navanītam) \in 7-Z38 48 (Divyamaṇi), 49 (Dhavaḷāmbari) \in 7-Z18. The system contains exactly two unordered Z-related Melakarta pairs, {40,48} and {40, 49}, both with interval-class vector (4, 3, 4, 4, 4, 2).
Proof. A direct computational enumeration of the \binom{72}{2}=2556 pairs finds 121 pairs sharing an interval-class vector. The 121 same-IC pairs can be analytically derived. The 72 scales realize four inversionally symmetric Forte classes: 7-22 (size 3), 7-33 (size 2), 7-34 (size 4), and 7-35 (size 6). Because every scale within these classes is related to every other scale by both T_n and T_nI simultaneously, the number of pairs falling into the "Both" category is the sum of the combinations: \binom{3}{2} + \binom{2}{2} + \binom{4}{2} + \binom{6}{2} = 3 + 1 + 6 + 15 = 25 pairs. The remaining 94 pairs originate from classes lacking inversional symmetry, which bifurcate into enantiomorphic halves. Summing the T_n-only combinations within the halves and the T_nI-only combinations crossing the halves yields exactly 36 T_n-only pairs and 58 T_nI-only pairs. Finally, adding the 2 pairs exhibiting the Forte Z-relation completes the ledger: 36 + 58 + 25 + 2 = 121 pairs.
A direct check against the Forte catalog confirms that E(40) has prime form \mathtt{(0,1,2,4,5,7,8)} = 7-Z38, while E(48) and E(49) have prime form \mathtt{(0,1,2,3,5,8,9)} = 7-Z18. The pair {48, 49} is T_{n}I-related (in fact T_{7}I-related) within 7-Z18; it is therefore not a Z-pair.
To understand why the other two heptachord Z-pairs cataloged by Allen Forte—specifically 7-Z12/7-Z36 and 7-Z17/7-Z37—are structurally forbidden, we must examine the rigid constraints of the Melakarta system. Every Melakarta scale must contain the fixed Sa (semitone 0) and Pa (semitone 7). Furthermore, the gap rules within the tetrachords prohibit certain dense chromatic clusters. For example, 7-Z12 has the prime form \mathtt{(0,1,2,3,4,7,9)}, which contains five consecutive chromatic semitones (0,1,2,3,4). The Melakarta structure can accommodate at most four consecutive semitones (e.g., N3, S, R1, R2), making the 5-semitone cluster of 7-Z12 impossible to realize. Similar tetrachord constraints strictly prevent the realization of 7-Z17 and its Z-mate, leaving 7-Z18/7-Z38 as the unique Z-relation bounded within the 72-scale system. \square
7 The vivadi classification revisited
Carnatic theorists partition the 72 Melakartas into two traditional classes: the vivadi (dissonance-prone) Melakartas and the avivadi (non-dissonant) Melakartas. This section formalises the vivadi predicate in our bit-level framework, identifies a precise predicate that exactly reproduces the classical 40-element vivadi set, and offers a perceptual interpretation of the fourteen Melakartas whose status depends delicately on the predicate choice.
7.1 The classical vivadi predicate
The term vivadi goes back to Śārṅgadeva's Sangita Ratnakara (c. 1225) (Śārṅgadeva, c. 1225; Widdess, 1988), where it denotes a pair of scale degrees separated by one śruti (microtonal step). Govindācārya's Sangraha Chudamani (Govindācārya, c. 1750) extended the concept to Melakarta labels. Sambamurthy's twentieth-century formalisation (Sambamurthy, 1963-1973, Vol. III, ch. 2) gives the standard count of forty vivadi Melakartas. These classical accounts converge on the forty-count but do not, to our knowledge, offer a bit-level predicate that reproduces it.
7.2 A naive bit-level predicate
A Melakarta's encoding has its R-G type in bits 10-7 (popcount-2 nibble in {\mathtt{0x3}, \mathtt{0x5}, \mathtt{0x6}, \mathtt{0x9}, \mathtt{0xA}, \mathtt{0xC}}) and its D-N type in bits 3-0. Call a nibble tension-1 if its two set bits are adjacent in the four-bit window.
Definition 7.1 (Naive vivadi). A Melakarta is naively vivadi iff its R-G or D-N nibble belongs to {\mathtt{0x3}, \mathtt{0x6}, \mathtt{0xC}}.
Proposition 7.2. Exactly fifty-four Melakartas are naively vivadi, in excess of the classical count of forty by fourteen. Proof. By inclusion-exclusion: 3\cdot6\cdot2+6\cdot3\cdot2-3\cdot3\cdot2=36+36-18=54.
7.3 The extremal-nibble predicate
Definition 7.3 (Extremal vivadi). A Melakarta is extremally vivadi iff its R-G or D-N nibble belongs to the two-element set {\mathtt{0x3}, \mathtt{0xC}}—the two tension-1 patterns whose set bits sit at the boundary of the nibble window.
Theorem 7.4. Exactly forty Melakartas are extremally vivadi. This matches the classical count of Govindācārya and Sambamurthy. Proof. By inclusion-exclusion: 2\cdot6\cdot2+6\cdot2\cdot2-2\cdot2\cdot2=24+24-8=40.
Proposition 7.5 (Fourteen middle-chromatic Melakartas). The fourteen Melakartas that are naively but not extremally vivadi form the set X = {10, 16, 20, 21, 22, 23, 28, 46, 52, 56, 57, 58, 59, 64}. These are exactly the Melakartas containing the nibble \mathtt{0x6} in either the R-G or D-N position, and not simultaneously \mathtt{0x3} or \mathtt{0xC} in the other.
7.4 A perceptual interpretation
The ends-versus-middle distinction in the nibble patterns admits a perceptual hypothesis. Consider a Melakarta with R-G nibble \mathtt{0xC}=(R_{1},G_{1}). The scale contains semitones 1 and 2, both within a narrow chromatic window immediately above Sa. The ever-present drone on Sa will beat against these tones at the audible rate of a semitone's frequency difference, producing the perceptual roughness classical theory associates with vivadi. Analogous roughness arises for \mathtt{0x3}, where the tones sit immediately below the next structurally fixed scale-tone (M_{1}). For \mathtt{0x6}=(R_{2},G_{2}), semitones 2 and 3 sit in the interior of the lower tetrachord, neither immediately adjacent to Sa nor to M_{1}—beating with the drone is substantially weaker. The analogous hypothesis for the upper tetrachord is symmetric.
We emphasise that this is a perceptual hypothesis, not a theorem; it appeals to proximity-to-drone reasoning in consonance-dissonance theory (Sethares, 2005) but has not been independently validated against psychoacoustic data.
8 Cross-cultural correspondences
8.1 Hindustani thaats and Western modes
The six diatonic modes collectively realise the Forte class 7-35. Hungarian minor (mela 57) and Double harmonic major (mela 15) both sit in 7-22: they are T_{7}-related in pitch-class terms, with mela 57 the fourth mode of mela 15 (applying the rotation x\mapsto x-5 \bmod 12 to {0, 1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11} yields {7,8,11,0,2,3,6} = {0,2,3,6,7,8,11}, i.e. mela 57 at transposition T_{7} of mela 15).
9 Prior art and positioning
9.1 Positioning of our five contributions
We itemise the five specific contributions of this paper that we believe are new, together with their relationship to the most-closely-anticipating prior sources.
(N1) Klein-four group structure. The generators K_{1} and K_{2} are individually known: K_{1} is Venkaṭamakhin's two-factor, K_{2} visually anticipated in Mukund's chart. Their composition into a Klein four-group acting freely on the 72-set with 18 orbits of size 4 appears to be new.
(N2) The 9-regular Hamming graph. The Hamming metric on 12-bit heptachord codes is a standard measure (Samplaski, 2005), but its restriction to the 72-Melakarta subset has not been studied.
(N3) A constructive Gray-code Hamiltonian path. The existence of a Gray code on the ambient \binom{12}{7} heptachord space is classical. Its existence on the 72-Melakarta subset, with the minimum-crossing property, is new to this paper.
(N4) Uniqueness of the Z-relation. Per-scale Forte-class and Z-label data are implicit in Ring (accessed 2024–2026) for all 12-bit scales. The observation that exactly one of the three heptachord Z-pairs is realised by the Melakartas, carried by {40, 48, 49}, appears not to have been explicitly stated in Ring's catalog or elsewhere. Our Theorem 6.2 makes this precise.
(N5) The extremal-nibble vivadi predicate. The 40-element vivadi count is classical (Govindācārya, c. 1750; Sambamurthy, 1963-1973). The refinement to a bit-structural predicate—nibble \in\{\mathtt{0x3}, \mathtt{0xC}\}—and the identification of the 14-mela exception set X with a perceptual explanation are new.
10 Empirical test and limitations
10.1 Empirical correlation with janya counts
The structural invariants of Sections 3-7 partition the 72 Melakartas. If any partition is musically meaningful, we expect correlation with an independent measure of compositional productivity. We use per-Melakarta janya count from the Wikipedia list (Wikipedia contributors, 2026) (902 janyas attributed to the 72 parents, snapshot 22 April 2026; see Appendix C for a permanent record of the counts) and test four structural predictors using Spearman's \rho.
Result 1 (Forte-class population). Forte-class population size is a robust positive predictor: \rho=+0.46, p<10^{-4}. Excluding Māyāmāḷavagauḷa: \rho=+0.45; excluding the top six Melakartas: \rho=+0.45.
Result 2 (Klein-four orbit membership). Klein-four orbit membership captures approximately 60% of the log-scale variance in janya count across orbits. The top three orbits account for 52% of all 902 janyas; the top orbit alone ({15, 22, 51, 58}) accounts for 194.
Result 3 (Extremal-vivadi status). Avivadi Melakartas have mean janya count 16.0 vs. 8.2 for extremal-vivadi, a two-fold descriptive effect. Rank correlation \rho=-0.20, p=0.09, not reaching conventional significance.
11 Conclusion
The 72 Melakartas, encoded under mirrored endianness as popcount-seven vectors in \mathbb{F}_{2}^{12}, admit a rich interlocking collection of algebraic and combinatorial symmetries: a free Klein-four action with 18 orbits (Section 3); a 9-regular distance-2 graph with fully determined distance distribution (Section 4); an explicit Gray-code Hamiltonian path with minimum madhyama crossings (Section 5); a unique realised Forte Z-relation (Section 6); and a bit-structural refinement of the classical vivadi predicate (Section 7). The five contributions formalise a classical taxonomy in modern algebraic-combinatorial language without distorting any of its classical content.
